I felt like this was a very good scrutiny of white/rich privilege.<br /><br />It was in your face- the bodies of people of color and the poor are used to supplement the rich white people who can afford such things.<br /><br />A lot of people are taking the wrong message away from this, as in 'what the protagonist is doing is okay' and it is obviously not, which is why the movie is set up as a horror, and not a feel good film.<br /><br />It shows that when people have money and power, they will act in a corrupt and inhumane fashion to save themselves and the ones that are closest to them.<br /><br />It hit the point home very well.<br /><br />The only place where it really lost me is that the main protagonist (our stand-in of course) was shown to not know what was going on, and the only other relatable character in the home seemed to know but didn't talk to her about it openly. The people in the home were awful. It would have been a lot more realistic if all of the other 'villians' who knowingly take others body parts were nice and friendly all the time, because that is how real racists and people in power act until they are behind closed doors, though I guess you could say the community was a giant closed door.
